-     USERNAME
           A username may be up to 20 characters.  The acceptable char-
           acters consist of:
                - all alpha-numeric characters
                - the characters: <space> # $ * & , . - /
           Please note the following:
                - the dash "-" is ignored on auxilliary circuits
                - the comma ","  is used as a field  separator in CCITT
                  protocol and should not be included in usernames that
                  will be used through X gateways
0     ENTRY CHANGE DATE
           The entry  change date is the  date that the entry  was last
           changed (except for a password change), and may not be modi-
           fied directly.
0     PASSWORD CIPHER
           The  password may  be up  to 30  characters.  Any  character
           other than a  semicolon, null, rub-out, escape,  or carriage
           return may be used within a  password.  All lower case char-
           acters are translated to upper  case.  Note that commas ",",
           plus signs "+", colons ":",  and control characters are used
           in CCITT  protocol and should  not be included  in passwords
           that will be used through X gateways.
0     PASSWORD CHANGE DATE
           The password change  date is the date that  the password was
           last changed, and  may not be modified  directly.  Note that
           the password change date is  not updated unless the password
           is changed  to a  NEW value.   A change  in the  NO PASSWORD
           option (below) also  causes a change to  the password change
           date.
0     UNIVERSAL USER NUMBER (UUN)
           The UUN  is a number in  the range 0 to  37777777777 (octal)
           which uniquely identifies a user.  The  UUN for an entry can
           never change.
0     GLOBAL ACCOUNT NUMBER (GAN) - optional
           The GAN  is a number in  the range 0 to  37777777777 (octal)
           and is used to group users together under a single account.
0     CONTROL OPTIONS
0          ACCOUNT SUPERVISOR - optional
                Account supervisor license specifies  that the user may
                perform validation changes to users in its own GAN.
0          AUDITOR
                If the auditor  option is ON, the user  may display CUD
                information about any user.
-
-                                          CUD - MUD Contents    Page 6
0
0
1     Netval External Reference Specification          October 31, 1986


-          IGNORE HOST
                If  the  ignore host  option  is  ON, any  host  number
                entered when building  a circuit is ignored,  i.e., the
                home information  (in access  profile below)  specifies
                the default host or hosts  (sub-hosts are not ignored).
                An exception to this is if the user also has the TRANS-
                PARENT LOGIN (see below) option set.   If a TARGET PRO-
                FILE name  is used (see Supervisor  documentation), the
                ignore host option is, itself, ignored.
0          NETWORK ADMINISTRATOR
                Network administrator license specifies  that the vali-
                dator may  perform validation changes  to users  in any
                GAN, and various NETVAL utility functions.
0          NO PASSWORD
                If  the no  password  option is  ON,  the  user is  not
                required to  input a  password when  logging in.   This
                option forces the ignore host option (this may change).
0          OPERATOR
                If the operator option is ON, the user may perform NET-
                VAL operational and tape archive functions.
0          SHUT OVERRIDE
                If the shut override option is  ON, the user may access
                a host even if it is shut.
0          TRANSPARENT LOGIN
                If the  transparent login option  is ON, when  the user
                logs in, the  circuit is built through  the home, which
                has been set up to be a  gateway, and the login contin-
                ues in the other network.  The username, any host input
                and  possibly a  password  is passed  to  be the  login
                string to the other network.
0     DISTRICT - optional
           The district, a number in the range 1 - 4095, is another way
           to group users.
