                                           OPERATOR Commands    Page 40
0
0
1     Netval External Reference Specification          October 31, 1986


-     If a tape unit is ATTACHED explicitly by the ATTACH command (Sec-
      tion 8.12.2), it remains ATTACHED until it is DETACHED explicitly
      by the DETACH command (Section 8.12.4).  Any Netval ARCHIVE vali-
      dator may use  (and therefore may also DETACH)  an attached tape,
      as long as no other validator has the tape ASSIGNED.
0     If  a tape  unit is  ASSIGNED explicitly  to a  validator by  the
      ASSIGN command  (Section 8.12.1), it  remains ASSIGNED  until the
      validator explicitly DEASSIGNS  the unit by the  DEASSIGN command
      (Section 8.12.3) OR  leaves the Netval system (by  logging out or
      becoming  disconnected).   If a  Netval  user  still has  a  tape
      ASSIGNED when he logs out, Netval will notify him of the unit.
0     During any Netval ARCHIVE command that  accesses a tape unit, the
      unit is necessarily both ATTACHED  and ASSIGNED for the validator
      (implicitly if not by an explicit  command).  If reserved implic-
      itly, the tape unit is reserved for the Netval slot and the vali-
      dator FOR THE DURATION OF THE COMMAND ONLY.  At the completion of
      the command, the unit will have the  same status as it did before
      the command.  If  the unit had previously been  ATTACHED, it will
      remain ATTACHED.
0     When a  validator enters or leaves  the ARCHIVE sub-system  he is
      shown a summary of the status of all  tape units in use; the DIS-
      PLAY STATUS  command (Section 8.12.5.2) may  also be used  to see
      the summary.
